# Step 4: Top 10 countries by total cases (latest date available)

# Get the latest date in the dataset
latest_date = df['date'].max()

# Filter for the latest available data
latest_data = df[df['date'] == latest_date]

# Select only countries (exclude continents, World, etc.)
latest_data_countries = latest_data[latest_data['iso_code'].str.len() == 3]

# Pick top 10 countries by total cases
top10_cases = latest_data_countries.nlargest(10, 'total_cases')

# Step 5: Vaccination Analysis

# Line Chart 1: Total vaccinations over time
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

    country_data = df_countries[df_countries['location'] == country]
    plt.plot(country_data['date'], country_data['total_vaccinations'], label=country)

plt.title("COVID-19 Vaccination Rollout (Total Vaccinations)", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Total Vaccinations")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()


# Line Chart 2: % of population vaccinated (if available)
if 'people_vaccinated_per_hundred' in df_countries.columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    for country in countries:
        country_data = df_countries[df_countries['location'] == country]
        plt.plot(country_data['date'], country_data['people_vaccinated_per_hundred'], label=country)

    plt.title("COVID-19 Vaccination Progress (% of Population Vaccinated)", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("% of Population Vaccinated")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()
else:
    print("Column 'people_vaccinated_per_hundred' not available in dataset.")


# Pie Charts: Vaccinated vs. Unvaccinated (latest snapshot for each country)
for country in countries:
    latest_data = df_countries[df_countries['location'] == country].dropna(subset=['people_vaccinated_per_hundred']).tail(1)

    if not latest_data.empty:
        vaccinated = float(latest_data['people_vaccinated_per_hundred'])
        unvaccinated = 100 - vaccinated

        plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
        plt.pie(
            [vaccinated, unvaccinated],
            labels=['Vaccinated %', 'Unvaccinated %'],
            colors=['#4CAF50','#FF7043'],
            autopct='%1.1f%%',
            startangle=90
        )
        plt.title(f"{country} - Vaccination Coverage (Latest)", fontsize=14)
        plt.show()
    else:
        print(f"No vaccination percentage data available for {country}.")

import plotly.express as px

# Step 6: Choropleth Map - Global total cases (latest date)
latest_date = df['date'].max()
df_latest = df[df['date'] == latest_date]

# Filter needed columns
map_data = df_latest[['iso_code', 'location', 'total_cases', 'total_vaccinations']].dropna(subset=['total_cases'])

# Choropleth for total cases
fig_cases = px.choropleth(
    map_data,
    locations="iso_code",
    color="total_cases",
    hover_name="location",
    color_continuous_scale="Reds",
    title=f"Global COVID-19 Total Cases as of {latest_date}"
)
fig_cases.show()

# Choropleth for total vaccinations
fig_vax = px.choropleth(
    map_data.dropna(subset=['total_vaccinations']),
    locations="iso_code",
    color="total_vaccinations",
    hover_name="location",
    color_continuous_scale="Greens",
    title=f"Global COVID-19 Total Vaccinations as of {latest_date}"
)
fig_vax.show()

Step 7: Insights & Reporting¶

Key Insights¶

  1. The United States shows the highest cumulative vaccination rollout compared to Kenya and India.
  2. Kenya had relatively lower vaccination coverage, with less than X% of the population vaccinated by [latest date].
  3. Daily new cases peaked around mid-2021 for both USA and India, while Kenya’s peaks were smaller but noticeable.
  4. The global choropleth map clearly highlights how cases and vaccinations are unevenly distributed.
  5. Death rate (total_deaths / total_cases) appears significantly higher in some countries, suggesting healthcare capacity differences.

Conclusion¶

This analysis of global COVID-19 data highlights how the pandemic has evolved across different countries:

  • The United States had the highest reported cases and vaccinations overall.
  • India experienced very sharp peaks in daily new cases, especially during mid-2021.
  • Kenya had fewer cases overall but also much lower vaccination coverage compared to USA and India.
  • Vaccination progress has been uneven globally, with high-income countries leading early rollouts.
  • Death rates vary widely across countries, suggesting differences in healthcare infrastructure, reporting accuracy, and demographics.

These findings emphasize the importance of timely vaccination campaigns and continuous monitoring of pandemic data.
